<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-701-768  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 701 768.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  August 1990 v7 n8 p153(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Backing up through a window. (overview to evaluations of theEmerald Systems VAST tape backup system and the InternationalMachine Control Systems MousePen) (Hardware Review) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Koontz, Charles P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The introduction of Microsoft Windows 3.0 disrupted the LAN TIMESTesting Center's evaluation of networking products that run underWindows.andP;  Applications designed for earlier versions of Windowsoften do not run under 3.0, and it served no purpose to testapplications that did not maintain functionality.andP;  One productthat experienced only minimal degradation is the Emerald Systems'VAST tape back-up system.andP;  The vendor plans to release a systemspecifically for Windows 3.0 in the fall of 1990.andP;  In the processof the evaluations, an International Machine Control SystemsMousePen was obtained and became the primary input device used fortesting.andP;  A review of the MousePen is also included.andP;  Products areevaluated individually for ease of installation, features, anddocumentation and support, and rated in each category and overallon a scale of from one to five, with five being the best.andP;  Anyproduct scoring an overall total of 13 or more is awarded the LANTIMES Recommended for Networking Award.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Emerald Systems Corp. (products)International Machine Control Systems Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Emerald Systems VAST (Tape drive)International Machine Control Systems MousePen (Mouse).andO;Topic:     EvaluationBack-Up SystemsMiceNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>